    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-04-24T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-04-24T23:00:00-05:00" n="526"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d526">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                        >Baker, Charles</persName>/79: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow (<persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_AWA1" type="from">Adams</persName>) to the <gloss
                            type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-25T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >April 25, 1932—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received April 25—5:50
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>49. 1. Mr. <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AGF1">G. Findlay Andrew</persName> of
                    the National Flood Relief Commission has now definitely initiated negotiations
                    with the Communists who hold <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                        >Baker</persName>. <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AGF1">Andrew</persName>
                    is also seeking to obtain the release of Father <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_SH2">Sands</persName> (British) who was captured on
                    August 16, 1931, and who is held by the same group who hold <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>.</p>
                <p>2. <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AGF1">Andrew</persName>’s latest information
                    is that <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName> is well fed and
                    now has his own personal servant. I suggest that information in this paragraph
                    be given to <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s wife in
                    Oakland.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AWA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Adams</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
